  "prompt": "Can a country run without president?",
  "response": "Yes, a country can function without a president, depending on its system of government. Here are some scenarios:\n\n1. Parliamentary Systems\n- In countries like Germany, the United Kingdom, and India, a Prime Minister serves as head of government\n- A ceremonial President or monarch may exist, but they have limited executive power\n\n2. Interim Periods\n- Some countries have interim governments or caretaker administrations when a president is absent\n- Constitutional mechanisms exist to handle leadership transitions\n\n3. Collective Leadership\n- Some nations have collective leadership structures\n- Switzerland has a Federal Council where seven members rotate leadership annually\n\n4. Direct Democracy\n- Some small countries or entities can function with more decentralized decision-making\n\n5. Emergency Situations\n- During political crises or transitions, countries can temporarily operate without a president\n- Government institutions continue to function through established bureaucratic mechanisms\n\n6. Different Government Structures\n- Some countries have different leadership models\n- For example, diarchal systems with two leaders\n\nWhile a president provides centralized leadership, most modern governments have robust institutional frameworks that can continue functioning even without a single executive leader.\n\nThe specific ability to operate without a president depends on each country's constitutional and political system.",
